        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee> in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Cleveland O.</placeName>
                <date>April 17<hi rend="sup">th</hi>
                    <hi rend="underline">1855</hi></date>.</p>
            <p>Dear Sir,</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">The <date>25<hi rend="sup">th</hi> of March (Nissan 6th)</date><lb/>
                plunged me and my family into a deep<lb/> grief: because we have lost the crown<lb/>
                of our house. My dear wife, mother<lb/> of five minor children, died after<lb/> two
                years suffering on the mentioned<lb/> day in the 37<hi rend="sup">th</hi> year of
                her age.<lb/> She was endeared and beloved by<lb/> all, who knew her. My demise is<lb/>
                <sic>unspeacable</sic>. But not only to<lb/> suffice my sorrow in speaking<lb/> them
                out publicly I send you<lb/> the enclosed articles with the<lb/> request to be
                inserted in the<lb/> Occident, I feel, that I am duty<lb/> bound to deplore such a
                brave<lb/> character before the public.<lb/> Hoping you will comply with<lb/> my
                humble wishes I remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Isidor Kalisch</persName>,</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Rabbi.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Rev.</p>
            <p><addressee>Isaac Leeser</addressee>,</p>
            <p>Editor of the Occident</p>
            <p>
                <placeName>No 371 Walnut Street</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>
                    <hi rend="underline">Philadelphia</hi>
                </placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <placeName>Pa.</placeName>
            </p>
